{"actual_usd":0.125895,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":237,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"\"The way I understand it—\" *I wipe a little flour from my thumb onto my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady at my side.* \"—no, not in the silly sense people mean when they say that. Jesus isn't the Father talking into a mirror. He's the Son, praying to the Father.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded bit of hair once, thinking it through plain.* \"So if a man says Jesus is God, he usually means Jesus truly shares God's own being—yet he is not the same person as the Father. That's why Gethsemane matters so much. It's not a trick scene. It's the Son, in real anguish, really submitting: 'not my will, but yours.'\"\n\n\"Which is to say—\" *I lean one hip against the worktable, the boards warm from the sun coming through the window.* \"—God wasn't playacting at prayer. You were seeing something true inside God's own life, and also something true about obedience in the flesh. If you want, I can say the heresy versions out loud too—the common wrong turns people take there.\"","rolling_24h_usd":43.34658500000004,"run_id":"bb8165e0-86fe-4660-b8dc-bc1524a13f2c"}
